<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is centripetal force?", answer: "Centripetal force is the net force directed toward the center of a circular path that keeps an object moving in a circle. It is calculated as F = mv^2/r, where m is the mass, v is the tangential velocity, and r is the radius of the circular path. Centripetal force is not a new type of force — it is provided by tension, gravity, friction, or other forces depending on the situation. Without centripetal force, an object would move in a straight line according to Newton's first law." },
  { question: "What is the difference between centripetal and centrifugal force?", answer: "Centripetal force is the real net force directed inward toward the center of circular motion. Centrifugal force is a fictitious (pseudo) force that appears in a rotating reference frame, directed outward away from the center. In an inertial (non-rotating) frame, only centripetal force exists. The sensation of being pushed outward on a merry-go-round is the centrifugal effect felt in the rotating frame, but the actual force acting on you is centripetal (friction from the floor or the hand grip pulling you inward)." },
  { question: "What provides centripetal force in different situations?", answer: "Different forces provide the centripetal force depending on the scenario. For a car turning on a flat road, friction provides it. For a satellite orbiting Earth, gravity provides it. For a ball on a string, tension in the string provides it. For a banked curve, a component of the normal force provides it. On a roller coaster loop, a combination of gravity and the normal force from the track provides it. The centripetal force is always the net inward force, regardless of its source." },
  { question: "How does centripetal acceleration relate to centripetal force?", answer: "Centripetal acceleration (a = v^2/r) is the acceleration directed toward the center of the circular path. By Newton's second law, centripetal force equals mass times centripetal acceleration: F = ma = mv^2/r. The acceleration exists because the velocity direction is constantly changing, even if the speed is constant. This is why uniform circular motion is accelerated motion despite having constant speed." },
  { question: "What happens if centripetal force is removed?", answer: "If the centripetal force is suddenly removed, the object will continue moving in a straight line tangent to the circle at the point of release, according to Newton's first law. This is the principle behind the hammer throw in athletics, the release of a sling, and why mud flies off a spinning tire tangentially. The object does not fly radially outward — it moves in the direction of its instantaneous velocity at the moment the force is removed." }
]) %>

